1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 (5. Bd3 {is an alternative move
order. After} O-O ({However, Black has an extra option} 5... Nc6 $5 {which can
be avoided with the more flexible move order 5.Nf3 0-0 6.Bd3.}) 6. Nf3 $5 {
we transpose into the main line.} (6. Nge2 {is the genuine Seirawan variation.}
)) 5... O-O {White has many ways to fight against the King's Indian Defencse.
In this database, I will suggest a fresh approach with} 6. Bd3 $5 {At first,
this seems like a mixup between the two different systems. Usually, we develop
our bishop and knight either in the ''classical'' Be2-Nf3 or the ''Seirawan''
Bd3-Ne2 formation. By comparison, Bd3-Nf3 (which I decided to name the
''Neo-Seirawan'' variation) seems less principled because it allows Black to
pin the knight with Bg4. However, things are not that simple for Black after
this move, as we will see. The first strong player to try this system was the
ever-creative GM Daniil Dubov back in 2020. His opponent was no less than
Magnus Carlsen, and Dubov scored a thematic win. This game caught the
attention of other grandmasters, including Carlsen himself. The World Champion
used 6.Bd3 in two blitz/rapid games, as well as Hikaru Nakamura. In classical
chess, it scored particularly well in the hands of grandmasters Dardha and
Bernadskiy. So far, most Black players have been reacting in less than optimal
ways to the Neo-Seirawan variation, which partly explains why White have been
getting very good positions (and scoring over 65% on 2400+ level) with it. The
obvious advantage of developing the bishop to d3 instead of the more usual e2
is that it helps White control the key e4-square. Moreover, it helps White
fight against Black's thematic f5-break if the centre gets blocked with ...
e7-e5/d4-d5. The bishop is also placed well on d3 in the Benoni/Benko
structures, should Black go for the ...c7-c5 instead. The obvious downside is
that it allows the Bg4 pin, but this is not such a big issue as it might seem
at first. The database is broken down into two parts: 1) Theoretical material
in the first nine chapters; and 2) Seven typical central structures with
lightly annotated key games.} ({By comparison to 6.Bd3 Bg4 7.Be2! line, White
is up a tempo in the Bg4 line of the Classical KID:} 6. Be2 Bg4 {This line is
considered clearly advantageous for White after} 7. Be3 Nfd7 8. Qd2 {We don't
mind playing a similar position down a tempo after 6.Bd3 Bg4 since we still
have good chances to obtain an advantage out of the opening.}) {The most
principled reply is} 6... Bg4 {pinning the f3-knight in order to weaken
White's defence of the d4-pawn. We will discuss this essential reply in
Chapters 1 through 3.} ({In Chapters 4 and 5, we examine a ''pure'' King's
Indian approach with} 6... e5 7. d5 {In this type of position, the bishop is
placed quite well on the b1-h7 diagonal, as discussed earlier. When attacked
by a knight from f4 or c5, it can simply retreat to c2. The lines below
illustrate typical ideas for both sides in the arising middlegame.} a5 {
(Chapter 5)} (7... Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] (Chapter 4)} 8. O-O Nf4 9. Bc2 {[%csl Gc2]
[%cal Yc2f5,Rf7f5]} Nd7 10. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Gg2g3]} Nf6 11. g3 {[%cal Gf3h4,
Gh4g2,Yc1e3,Yc4c5] Once we have expelled the knight from f4, we will take
prophylactic measures against Black's kingside play and prepare our own
expansion on the queenside.}) 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bc2 Nc5 10. a3 Bd7 11. b3 {
[%cal Ra5a4]} Nh5 12. Rb1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb3b4,Gf7f5] We have a fairly
typical KID middlegame where both sides look to develop active play on the
respective wings. The white bishop is placed quite conveniently on c2, not
only to fight against the f5-break but also to prepare b3-b4 by covering
important light squares on the queenside.}) ({In Chapter 4, we also take a
look at} 6... Nbd7) ({and} 6... Na6 {In both cases, the game usually
transposes into the 6...e5 7.d5 line after} 7. O-O e5 8. d5 {although White
has some more flexibility here.}) ({The Benoni approach with} 6... c5 7. d5 {
is covered in Chapters 6 through 8. Black usually continue} e6 ({In Chapter 6,
we focus on the less popular continuations, such as} 7... Bg4) ({and} 7... e5)
8. h3 {This way, we ensure that Bg4 is not an option anymore.} ({White can
also transpose into other lines covered in the database with} 8. O-O exd5 9.
exd5 Bg4 10. h3 ({or} 10. Be2)) {Black can either open the centre at once with}
8... exd5 ({or keep the tension with} 8... Na6 {(Chapter 6)} 9. O-O Nc7 {
A waiting game ensues, where both sides are trying to get in useful developing
moves (Re1, Be3, Qd2 for White; Re8, Rb8 for Black) before determining the
central structure. Still, the side with more space typically has the upper
hand.}) 9. exd5 Re8+ 10. Be3 {By transposition, a well-known theoretical
position of the Benoni is reached. White's space advantage cannot be disputed,
so Black usually tries to create counterplay on the dark-square complex either
by playing} Bh6 {(Chapter 8)} ({or the more flashy} 10... Rxe3+ $5 {(Chapter 7)
} 11. fxe3 Qe7 12. O-O Nbd7 {Black can claim a positional compensation for the
exchange since it's not easy for White to break the dark-square blockade. We
will examine a relatively rare approach} 13. Qe1 $5 {[%cal Ge1h4]}) ({Black
has also tried a few other moves in this tabiya, such as} 10... Nbd7 {[%cal
Gd7e5]}) ({and} 10... Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4] which are also covered in Chapter 7.})
11. O-O Bxe3 12. fxe3 Qe7 (12... Rxe3 $2 {is not advisable as it gives White a
huge attack after} 13. Qd2 $40 {[%cal Gd2h6]}) (12... Nbd7 13. e4 Rf8 $5 {
[%cal Gf6e8,Gd7e5,Ye8d6] is an interesting alternative, but we will see how to
deal with this idea, as well.}) 13. e4 Nbd7 {This position was reached in
numerous games in this line. While there is nothing wrong with a patient
approach based on the space advantage, such as doubling the rooks on the
f-file and manoeuvring our pieces toward the kingside, I recommend a more
direct approach with} 14. Nb5 $5 ({or even the immediate} 14. e5 $5) 14... Rf8
15. e5 $1 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. d6 {with promising initiative for a pawn.}) ({
The main subject of Chapter 9 is the provocative} 6... Nc6 {attacking White's
soft spot on d4. We should not hesitate with} 7. d5 Nb4 8. Be2 e6 {Black's
main strategic idea in this line is to undermine the white pawn centre. Still,
I believe that White keeps an edge after} 9. O-O Re8 (9... exd5 10. cxd5 a5 11.
a3 Na6 12. Be3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] looks pleasant for White.}) 10. dxe6 $1 Bxe6 11.
Nd4 {Now, we have something akin to the classical KID with early exd4. These
positions can be tactically tricky, but this shouldn't deter us from playing
principled chess with the extra space and good development.} Nc6 (11... Bd7 12.
f3) 12. Be3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 {We examine this and a few other branches in more
detail in this chapter.}) ({Finally, a few rare but reasonable KID setups,
such as} 6... c6 7. O-O a6 ({and} 7... Na6) 8. h3 b5 {are also covered in the
final chapter, although these should not pose a problem to White's opening
ambitions.}) 7. Be2 $1 {I believe that it is this move that drew the attention
of the pioneer of this variation, Daniil Dubov, and other players that
followed in his footsteps. Yes, it's not the best policy to waste a tempo
playing with the same piece in the opening, but in concrete terms, we have
gotten a well-known theoretical position, only with Black to move. The key
issue here is that White usually gets a pleasant advantage if it's his move
here (see my notes to 6.Be2 Bg4 line above!) . So, we might just check the
same position with Black to play to see if White can still get an edge. As it
turns out, Black needs to tread very carefully to even think about equalizing
in this line.} Nfd7 {is the main and best move, clearing the long diagonal to
attack the d4-pawn, followed by Nc6.} ({The immediate} 7... Nc6 {(Chapter 1)
is less convincing because of} 8. d5 Bxf3 {and now both the sharp} 9. gxf3 $5 (
{and a more positional} 9. Bxf3 Ne5 10. Be2 {should give White the upper hand
in the middlegame.}) {This dynamic recapture puts White on a fast-track to a
surprising kingside attack:} 9... Ne5 10. f4 Ned7 11. h4 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gf4f5,
Gh4h5]}) ({Black could still opt for the Benoni structure with} 7... c5 {
(Chapter 1)} 8. d5 e6 ({It's worth noting that the Benko-like pawn sacrifice} 
8... b5 9. cxb5 a6 {is neutralized with} 10. a4 $1 axb5 11. Bxb5 $16) 9. O-O
exd5 10. exd5 {In this version, Black typically trades his ''bad'' bishop} Bxf3
11. Bxf3 {followed by} Nbd7 {[%cal Gf6e8,Gf7f5,Gd7e5] initiating play on the
dark squares. For that reason, I prefer} 12. g3 $5 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gf3e2,Gf2f4,
Yc1d2,Yd1c2] among several reasonable development schemes.}) 8. Be3 {The main
reply, corresponding to the 6.Be2 Bg4 7.Be3 line.} ({There is also something
to be said about} 8. Ng1 $5 {(Chapter 2) , a move that's virtually never been
seriously tested. My analysis shows that White has at least a minimal edge in
all lines, the main one being} Bxe2 9. Ngxe2 e5 10. d5 a5 (10... f5 11. exf5
gxf5 12. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 11. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 8... Bxf3 {Black
eliminates one of the defenders of the key d4-square.} ({White is not troubled
by} 8... e5 9. d5 a5 {One of the ways to get a stable advantage is} 10. h3 Bxf3
11. Bxf3 f5 12. h4 f4 13. Bd2) 9. Bxf3 Nc6 {As Black threatens to establish
his knight on d4 after ...e7-e5, it's best to proceed with} 10. d5 Na5 {
(Chapter 3)} (10... Bxc3+ $5 {(Chapter 2)} 11. bxc3 Na5 {is a riskier approach,
and I believe that White should accept the challenge by continuing} 12. O-O $1
Nxc4 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Be2 Ncb6 15. Qd4 {[%csl Ye2,Rg8,Yh6][%cal Gf2f4] with a
strong compensation for the pawn in the view of the bishop pair and attacking
chances on the kingside.}) 11. Be2 Nb6 {The knights look awkward on b6 and a5,
but the c4-pawn is very vulnerable. Fortunately, we can defend it by tactical
means.} 12. Bd4 $1 Bxd4 (12... Naxc4 {fails to} 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15.
Qd4+ Ne5 16. f4 $18) 13. Qxd4 {Black, in turn, has his own tactic that allows
him to keep a delicate balance.} c5 14. dxc6 e5 $1 {Black aims to secure an
outpost on d4 with this intermezzo.} (14... Nxc6 15. Qd2 {is a very pleasant
Maroczy bind for White.}) {All of this has already been featured in one
classical grandmaster game, El Debs, F (2553) -Supi, L (2581) Osasco 2022
½-½ (43) . It was also analyzed among many branches in Gawain Jones'
super-popular King's Indian defence repertoire for Black. At this point, we
have two possibilities, the more enterprising} 15. Qd2 ({and the ''safe''} 15.
Qe3 {when White can obtain a slight structural advantage after} bxc6 16. c5)
15... bxc6 (15... Nxc6 {releases the tension from c4, presenting White with an
opportunity to attack the vulnerable kingside with} 16. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5,
Rh7h5,Yg2g4]}) 16. b3 {[%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rd6,Rg6][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Ga1d1,Ya5b7,
Yb7c5,Yc5e6] with ideas like h4-h5, in order to exploit Black's weak dark
squares around the black king. If Black follows up in the right way, the
position should be roughly balanced thanks to his counterplay via the
d4-square. In conclusion, if Black navigates this rare line properly, at the
very least we get a playable middlegame with some initiative.} *

