1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 {As noted in the
introduction, this is the critical reply against 6.Bd3. White doesn't mind
losing a tempo with} 7. Be2 {to strengthen his defence of the d4-pawn. The
main reply is 7...Nfd7, but in this chapter, we will examine its alternatives.
Let's start with} c5 (7... e5 {was featured in a recent super-GM encounter,
but it's hardly a principled way to play with Black.} 8. d5 a5 9. Be3 Na6 10.
Nd2 {White gets everything he wants here. Black will not be in a good position
to play ...f7-f5 any time soon.} Bxe2 (10... Bd7 11. g4 $16) 11. Qxe2 Nd7 12.
g4 $1 Ndc5 13. O-O-O Qd7 14. h4 $16 {½-½ (68) Carlsen, M (2859) -Nakamura, H
(2768) Chess.com INT 2022}) (7... Nc6 {is a direct assault on the pawn, but
its drawback is that it allows White to win a tempo by advancing the pawn} 8.
d5 Bxf3 {It's not often the case that two recaptures are equally good. Here,
we have a pleasant choice between} 9. gxf3 $5 {This would be a good choice if
we are in the mood to attack.} ({and} 9. Bxf3 {which leads to a more
''classical'' type of middlegame with a space advantage and the bishop pair
advantage.} Ne5 ({A queenside diversion with} 9... Na5 10. Be2 c6 {doesn't
quite work because of} 11. b4 $1 Nxc4 12. Bxc4 cxd5 13. Bb3 $1 $16) 10. Be2 {
Black can undermine the centre in one of two typical ways, but the verdict is
the same: White has a pleasant edge in the arising middlegames.} e6 (10... c6
11. O-O Rc8 12. f4 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3]}) 11. O-O Re8 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 exd5 14.
cxd5 $14 {[%csl Yd5,Ge2,Ge3,Ye4]}) 9... Ne5 (9... Nb8 10. f4 {doesn't make a
big difference unless Black plays} e6 (10... Nbd7 {transposes directly to the
9...Ne5 line}) {but White doesn't mind weakening the g6-pawn by playing} 11.
dxe6 fxe6 12. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5]} Qe8 13. Be3 Nbd7 14. Qd2 $40 {
[%cal Ge1c1,Yg1g7,Yh4h5]}) 10. f4 Ned7 11. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5,Gf4f5]} h5
12. Rg1 c6 13. Be3 {It's important to mobilize our pieces before starting any
concrete actions on the kingside.} Qa5 14. Kf1 $36 {[%csl Yf1,Rg6][%cal Gf4f5,
Ge3d4]}) (7... Nfd7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6,Ye7e5] is covered in the next two
chapters.}) 8. d5 {The Benoni approach with} e6 {is pretty decent here since
Black will also get to trade off his problematic light-squared bishop.} ({
The same cannot be said for the Benko-gambit approach with} 8... b5 9. cxb5 a6
10. a4 $1 {This is a slight improvement} ({over} 10. bxa6 {although Black's
counterplay didn't seem sufficient even after} Nxa6 11. O-O Qb6 12. h3 Bxf3 13.
Bxf3 Nd7 14. Be2 Rfb8 15. a4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb5] 1-0 (43) Zhou, J (2619)
-Moradiabadi, E (2576) Burlingame 2017}) {After either} 10... axb5 ({or} 10...
Bxf3 11. Bxf3 axb5 12. Nxb5 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5]}) 11. Bxb5 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5]
White pieces form a solid barrier on the a- and b-files, seriously hindering
Black's ambitions to claim compensation for the pawn.}) ({or} 8... a6 9. O-O b5
10. cxb5 axb5 11. Bxb5 Na6 12. h3 Bd7 13. Bc4 $16 {Black doesn't have the
typical Benko counterplay on the queenside in this position.} Ne8 14. Bf4 Qb6
15. Qe2 Nec7 16. e5 Rfb8 17. b3 $18 {1-0 (35) Dardha,D (2533) -Mohammad,N 
(2429) Sitges 2021}) 9. O-O exd5 10. exd5 {In this position, Black has tried
many moves in practice. We will examine a few of the most logical ones. Before
that, let's just try to understand the strategic contours of this middlegame.
Black is going to exchange his light-squared bishop on f3, sooner or later.
This will allow him to get better access to dark squares like d4, e5 and h4.
He usually tries to exploit them with dynamic moves like Bd4, Qh4, and N/Be5,
often throwing the f7-f5- (f4) advance in the mix. White, on the other hand,
enjoys a long-term static advantage thanks to his extra space and the bishop
pair. Thus, his plan in the next phase of the game should be to neutralize the
opponent's activity on the dark squares. Once he has done that, he can proceed
to increase his positional advantage. Experience tells us that one of the best
ways to achieve that is to place our pieces in the ''second rank formation'':
g3, Kg2, Be2, Qc2, Bd2, often followed by f2-f4. We can see a perfect
application of this plan in the following continuation:} Bxf3 ({A young
Belgian GM Dardha, one of the leading experts of the Neo-Seirawan variation,
also eventually employed this setup in the following game:} 10... Re8 11. h3
Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nbd7 13. Bf4 Ne5 14. Be2 a6 15. a4 Qc7 16. Qc2 Re7 17. Bg5 h6 18.
Bd2 {[%csl Yc2,Yd2,Ye2][%cal Gg2g3,Gg1g2]} Rae8 19. Rfe1 g5 {[%csl Gf5,Gh5]
[%cal Rf2f4]} 20. g3 $1 Qd7 21. Kg2 $14 {[%cal Yc2g2] White has a perfect
piece setup, and can look forward to the next stage of the game. Meanwhile,
Black is quite cramped.} Nh7 22. b3 Nf8 23. Bh5 Neg6 24. Rxe7 Rxe7 25. Bg4 $16
{1-0 (55) Dardha,D (2520) -Erigaisi,A (2567) Peniche 2021}) (10... Nbd7 {
seems like the most flexible choice. I would recommend a useful non-committal
move} 11. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga1a3,Ga3h3,Ya4a5,Rd7b6,Rb7b5]} ({It might be better to
omit} 11. h3 {for the time being, as it can make our kingside structure a
little shaky, for example} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Ne8 13. Qc2 Qh4 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal
Rg2g3]}) {Let's see a sample line:} 11... Ne8 12. Ra3 a6 13. Re1 {We keep
making useful moves in anticipation of ...Bxf3.} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bd4 15. Be2 Ng7
16. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} Ne5 17. Rh3 $1 $36 {[%csl Rf6,Rh7][%cal Yc1g5,Ye4f6,
Ge4g5] looks nice for White.}) 11. Bxf3 Nbd7 12. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf3e2,Gg1g2]
This continuation seems a bit more accurate} ({than} 12. Re1 {which is not to
take away from Bernadskiy's nice win against GM Kadric.} Ne8 13. Be2 Be5 14. g3
f5 15. Bh6 Ng7 16. Qd2 Nf6 17. f3 Kh8 18. Bd3 $14 {1-0 (24) Bernadskiy,V (2587)
-Kadric,D (2584) Cattolica 2021}) 12... Ne8 13. Qc2 Ne5 14. Be2 f5 15. Kg2 Qd7
16. Bd2 {[%cal Yc2g2] The ''second-rank'' formation has been achieved. White
has a solid positional plus in the ensuing middlegame.} Nf6 17. Rae1 $14 {
[%csl Re6][%cal Ye2d1,Yc3e2,Ye2f4,Gf2f4]} *

