1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 7. Be2 Nfd7 {
[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6,Ye7e5] This is the most consistent way to continue
attacking the soft underbelly of the white position. Black doesn't commit his
central pawns yet, which would allow White to achieve a favourable blockade
with d4-d5.} 8. Be3 {This ''automatic'' move has a worthy alternative.} ({
White can also force a trade of light-squared bishops with} 8. Ng1 $5 Bxe2 9.
Ngxe2 {The knight resets to e2, which is a slightly inferior square compared
to f3. However, White has accomplished two goals with this manoeuvre. Firstly,
he strengthened his defence of the d4-pawn, basically eliminating Black's
plans to destabilize it with ...Nc6. Secondly, a trade of the light-squared
bishops is typically in White's favour in the King's Indian Defence. White LSB
is generally his most passive piece, while its black counterpart is often
instrumental in preparing the f5-break and defending the resulting weaknesses
on the light squares. Since the game material is very limited in this line, we
need to explore logical plans for both sides:} e5 (9... c5 10. d5 Ne5 $5 {
This seems to be the only way to break from passivity.} ({The only game I
found in this line continued} 10... Na6 11. O-O Nc7 {1-0 (34) Djuric, S (2464)
-Tratar, M (2478) Campillos 2007 and here we can easily squeeze Black with} 12.
a4 b6 13. Bg5 a6 14. f4 $36 {[%csl Re7][%cal Yd1d3] etc.}) 11. b3 b5 $1 {
A consistent follow-up. Black sacrifices the pawn 'a la Benko' to generate
some activity in an otherwise rather uninspiring position.} 12. cxb5 a6 13.
bxa6 c4 14. O-O Nxa6 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, although White
has several ways to keep an edge, such as} 15. Bg5 $5 Qc7 16. Nd4 $14 {[%csl
Re7][%cal Gc3b5,Gd4c6]}) (9... a6 10. O-O c6 {[%csl Rc1,Rd4][%cal Yb7b5,Yd6d5]
is an interesting approach, which makes all the more sense now that White
doesn't have the light-squared bishop. If Black could eventually push ...b5 or
...d5, he could get better control over the light squares and fix the white
pawns on the dark squares. Anyway, we don't have to allow that.} 11. a4 $1 a5
12. Bg5 $14) 10. d5 {I analyzed several reasonable moves here:} a5 (10... f5 {
is also very logical. After} 11. exf5 gxf5 12. O-O {Black has a choice between}
f4 {[%csl Rc1,Ge4,Rg7][%cal Yc3e4,Yf4f3] which has its pros and cons.} ({and} 
12... Qh4 13. f4 {[%csl Rf5] which leads to an interesting middlegame battle.
For example,} Nf6 14. Bd2 Nbd7 15. Nb5 Ne8 16. Rf3 $14) {White can take the
annoying f-pawn head on after} 13. f3 Kh8 14. Kh1 $1 $14 {[%csl Rf4][%cal
Gg2g3,Gf1g1]}) (10... Qh4 {[%cal Gg7h6] is strongly met by} 11. Ng1 $1 {
[%cal Gg1f3,Rg7h6] preventing the trade of the dark-squared bishops.} f5 12.
Nf3 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf3g5]}) 11. h4 $1 {This Alpha-Zero-like pawn advance
is a very important resource in a few other lines in this variation. We take
advantage of the knight's absence from f6 to soften up the black kingside. Our
king can often find safety on the queenside or even in the centre in these
closed positions, so we don't need to worry about this being a ''weakening''
move. Black can react in one of two ways:} h5 {This move comes with a price:
the g6-pawn and g5-square will be permanently weakened whenever Black pushes
the pawn to f5 (along with the usual e6-square) .} ({and} 11... f5 12. h5 f4
13. hxg6 hxg6 14. Ng1 $1 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gd1g4,Gg1f3,Yg4e6] The knight
returns to its initial square, once again. This time, it makes space for the
queen so that it can exploit the newly created weaknesses on the light squares.
} Na6 15. Qg4 Qe8 16. Nh3 {[%cal Yh3g5,Yg5e6]} Nf6 17. Qf3 $14) {This gives
White assurance that he can claim a slight edge even with modest developing
moves, for example} 12. Be3 Na6 13. Qc2 f5 14. f3 $14) 8... Bxf3 {The most
straightforward continuation.} ({Carlsen preferred} 8... e5 9. d5 a5 {in his
first encounter with this variation. However, White is spoiled for choice here,
with several promising replies. The simplest one is} 10. h3 $146 (10. Nd2 {
played by Dubov, is logical, but both players missed a key tactical detail
down the line:} Bxe2 11. Qxe2 f5 12. f3 Na6 (12... Bh6 $1 {[%cal Yd8h4] would
have taken advantage of the white king still being on e1. White doesn't really
