was Carlsen's choice.} Na6 9. Be2 {Here, Black could have obtained timely
counterplay with} f5 (9... Qe8 {was slow and unnecessary.} 10. Be3 f5 11. exf5
Bxf5 12. Ng5 Nb4 13. Nge4 Nf6 14. f3 $16 {½-½ (68) Carlsen,M (2864) -Aronian,
L (2775) Miami 2022}) 10. exf5 Bxf5 {[%csl Re2,Gf5][%cal Yf5b1] This is why
I'd prefer to keep our bishop on d3/c2.} 11. Be3 (11. Nh4 {doesn't work
because of} Bh3 $1 12. Bxh5 $6 gxh5 13. Qxh5 Nc5 $17 {[%csl Re1,Gh3][%cal
Gc5d3]}) 11... Nf6 $13 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gf6e4,Ye5e4] Black is very active.}) 8...
Nf4 (8... a5 {is also likely to transpose to the main line after} 9. Bc2 Na6
10. a3 Nc5 {etc.}) 9. Bc2 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Rf7f5] The bishop feels comfortable
on this square, still discouraging the f5-break. Black can try a few other
ideas, such as} Nd7 ({and} 9... c6 10. Be3 {although White doesn't mind it if
the queenside opens up:} cxd5 11. cxd5 Nd7 12. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Yc4,Rd6][%cal
Gd2c4,Ga2a4,Gc3b5]}) (9... f5 $6 {is premature because of} 10. Bxf4 exf4 11.
exf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Rxf5 13. Nb5 $16 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gb5d4]}) 10. Kh1 $1 {
[%cal Gg2g3] It's a good idea to do something about the opponent's most active
piece. This way, we prepare to push it out with g2-g3.} Nf6 11. g3 Nh3 12. Nh4
$14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gh4g2,Gc1e3,Yc4c5,Yf3f4,Rf7f5] White has the f5-break under
control. Moreover, he can strengthen his position with normal developing moves
and gradually prepare his queenside play or the f4-break, depending on the
circumstances. Let's consider a sample line that illustrates these ideas.} Ng4
$5 13. Qe2 Bh6 14. f3 Bxc1 15. Raxc1 Nh6 16. Qd2 (16. c5 $5 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]})
16... Ng5 17. Ng2 f5 18. f4 $1 exf4 19. Nxf4 fxe4 20. Nxe4 $14 {[%csl Ge6,Rg8,
Rh6]} *

