1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. O-O {
I believe that this is the most promising approach for White.} ({For some
reason, top players tend to prefer preparing a kingside attack with} 8. h3 {
[%cal Gg2g4] although after} Nh5 9. g3 Na6 10. Be3 {1-0 (55) Nakamura, H (2795)
-Amin, B (2567) Almaty 2022} Qe7 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] the arising middlegame
is all but clear.}) 8... Nbd7 {I believe that most people would automatically
go for the Nbd7/a6-c5 manoeuvre here,} ({but let's also consider a few
alternatives:} 8... Na6 9. a3 Bd7 10. Bc2 $1 {[%cal Ra5a4,Yc2a4] preventing 10.
..Nc5, 11...a4, while also keeping an option of trading the bishops via a4 in
certain cases.} c6 $5 {In this case, we can get a favourable transformation
with} 11. dxc6 {[%csl Rd6]} Bxc6 12. b3 Nc7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. a4 $14 {[%csl
Gc4,Rd6,Ge4][%cal Rb7b5,Rd6d5] White is better thanks to his strong central
bind. Let's examine a few possibilities to get a better feel for this
structure:} Na6 14. Ba3 Nc5 (14... Nb4 15. Qe2 Qb6 16. Rad1 Rfd8 17. Bb1 $14 {
[%cal Ga3c1]}) 15. Qe2 b6 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. Rfe1 $14 {with a gradual build-up.})
(8... Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5] is another way to prepare the f5-break.} 9. Bc2 Na6 ({
In the case of a slightly premature} 9... f5 {White immediately shows the
potential of the bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal with a resolute continuation} 10.
exf5 gxf5 11. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Rf5][%cal Gg5e6]} Qe7 12. g4 $1 $36 {[%csl Gc2,
Rf5,Rh7]}) 10. a3 f5 {This is a better moment to play it. As a matter of
principle, we should open the centre because our pieces are well-positioned
for it.} 11. exf5 gxf5 {[%csl Yc1,Yc2,Yc3,Yf3] In this position, nothing
really stops us from continuing with a standard plan of the queenside
expansion:} 12. b4 {[%csl Ra6,Ye5,Yf5][%cal Ga1b1,Rf5f4,Re5e4] The issue with
the e5-f5 pawn duo is that they are the strongest in their current formation.
However, as soon as one pawn moves forward, a huge weakness arises on the
neighbouring squares. For example,} Qf6 ({or} 12... e4 $6 13. Nd4 Qf6 14. Nce2
$16 {[%csl Yd4,Yf4]}) 13. Ne2 f4 14. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Ra8,Ye4,Re8][%cal
Ge2c3,Gc3e4,Yc4c5] A complex middlegame lies ahead. White's superior piece
coordination gives him better chances.}) 9. Bc2 Nc5 10. a3 (10. Rb1 $5 {
might be a more accurate move order as it avoids complications in the 10...a4
line (see below) , while keeping good chances to eventually transpose into the
main line after a subsequent a3, b3, etc. Ultimately, it's probably not a big
issue, but it's good to be aware of it.}) 10... Bd7 (10... a4 $5 {is an
interesting attempt to complicate matters early.} 11. Be3 Bd7 (11... Nfd7 {
is a different pawn sacrifice. Black gives away a pawn on the queenside to
launch a quick kingside attack.} 12. Nxa4 Nxa4 13. Bxa4 f5 14. Bg5 $1 Qe8 15.
Bc1 $5 {[%cal Yf3d2]} Qe7 16. Bc2 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gb2b4,Yf5f4,Yg6g5,Ga3a4]
Black will surely have some compensation due to the kingside attack prospects.
White's extra pawn is not on schedule to make an impact soon, so our advantage
is not large here.}) 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Re1 $1 {[%cal Gc2a4,Gf3e5]} (13. Nxe5 $2
{allows} Nxe4) {Black has only one way to defend both pawns,} 13... Qe8 {
[%cal Ye8e5,Yd7a4] Nevertheless, we get the upper hand with} 14. d6 $1 cxd6 15.
Qxd6 {[%csl Rc5,Re5][%cal Gd6c5,Gd6e5] Black loses one of the pawns by force.
Even so, after} Nh5 $14 {[%cal Yh5f4,Yf4e6,Yg7f8,Gf8f7,Gf7f6] he will obtain
some compensation on the dark squares since we don't have a dark-squared
bishop.}) 11. b3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb3b4] This is an improvement} ({over the
previously played} 11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Ba4 {½-½ (50) Paravyan, D 
(2629) -Murzin, V (2502) Cheboksary 2021 when Black could simply decline the
trade with} Bc8 $5 $13 {[%cal Gf7f5,Yg4h6]}) 11... Nh5 {The most natural
continuation.} ({White does well after both} 11... c6 12. dxc6 Bxc6 13. Re1 $14
{[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb7b5,Rd6d5]}) ({and} 11... Ne8 12. Rb1 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 14.
b4 axb4 15. axb4 {[%csl Gc2,Rc5][%cal Rc5a4,Rc5e4]} e4 16. Bg5 $1 {The crucial
intermezzo.} Qc8 17. Nd4 Nd3 18. Nce2 $16 {[%csl Rd3,Yd4]}) 12. Rb1 {[%csl Gc2]
[%cal Gb3b4] White is ready for the queenside break. We can see how
well-placed the bishop is on c2, as it simultaneously controls key squares
like b3, a4, and e4.} Qe8 {[%cal Gc5a4,Yb3b4] Black delays b3-b4 for a moment
with this typical queen move. However, it has some downsides, as well.} ({
In the case of the straigthforward} 12... f5 {we continue} 13. exf5 gxf5 14. b4
axb4 15. axb4 {[%csl Rc5]} Na6 16. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Gc2,Rf5,Rh5][%cal Gf3e5,
Yf3g5,Yf3h4,Yg2g3] with a very pleasant middlegame. Black is doing well only
optically. In reality, it's difficult for him to achieve active counterplay
due to the multiple weaknesses incurred, ironically, by the f5-break. For
instance:} Qe8 (16... Nf6 17. g3 Kh8 18. Nh4 {[%csl Rf5]}) 17. Nh4 e4 18. g4 $1
{[%csl Re4,Rf5]} fxg4 19. Nxe4) 13. Re1 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ye1e8] A useful prelude
to our queenside play. The queen will not feel comfortable on e8 while being
x-rayed by the white rook.} f5 14. exf5 gxf5 15. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Re8] This
knight sortie highlights another typical downside of queen's position on e8:
weakening of the c7-pawn.} ({White can also get an edge with a more
straightforward} 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Na4 17. Nxa4 Bxa4 18. Ng5 {[%csl Ge6]}
Bxc2 19. Qxc2 Qg6 20. Ne6 Rf7 21. Rb3 $14 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gb3h3]}) 15... Bxb5
{The trade on b5 comes with a big price - Black will bleed on the light
squares.} ({In the event of} 15... Rc8 {we can utilize the e-file pin by
playing} 16. Nbd4 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf3g5,Gb3b4] and if} Ne4 {we have} 17.
Nxf5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re4]}) 16. cxb5 $14 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb3b4] A perfect
example of Black's trouble with the light squares is the following line:} Qxb5
17. Nh4 $18 {[%csl Gc2,Rf5,Rh5] In conclusion, many lines examined here show
how effective the light-squared bishop is on the b1-h7 diagonal once the
centre opens up. This is one of the key strategic ideas behind the
Neo-Seirawan system.} *

