1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {This move is not
too popular against the Neo-Seirawan variation. Nevertheless, there will
always be KID players who like to play the Benoni structure, so we have to be
ready for it.} 7. d5 e6 {The most common reply, and the one that can lead into
a well-known (delayed) Benoni tabiya, examined in the following two chapters.}
({Let's examine the alternatives. Firstly,} 7... Bg4 {is quite logical. Black
exchanges his light-squared bishop before White can prevent it with h2-h3. In
response, we can simply transpose into a corresponding position from Chapter 1
by playing 8.Be2. Alternatively, we could also play} 8. h3 ({for} 8. Be2 $5 {
see Chapter 1: 6.Bd3 Bg4 7.Be2 c5 8.d5.}) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 10. O-O exd5 11.
exd5 {A similar position has been examined in the first chapter, so I'd like
to refer you there for the strategic analysis of this type of position. In
this instance, Black is likely to try to bring the knight to e5, with either}
Nbd7 ({or} 11... Nfd7 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Gf7f5] This way, he also prepares to
push ...f5. Regardless, White's plan remains the same: retreat his pieces
first, then launch the f-pawn.} 12. Qd1 {[%cal Gd3e2,Gf2f4,Yg2g3,Yg1g2,Yc1d2]}
Ne5 13. Be2 f5 14. f4 Nf7 15. Bd2 Nd7 16. Bd3 Re8 17. Qf3 a6 18. Rae1 $16 {
[%cal Gg2g4] ½-½ (51) Cvitan,O (2550) -Barbero,G (2480) Zuerich 1992. Both
sides have achieved their objectives, but White has the upper hand thanks to
the space advantage and the potential for a kingside initiative with g2-g4.})
12. Qd1 Nh5 {[%cal Yg7d4,Yd8h4,Yd7e5] This move is in sync with Black's
strategy to generate play on the dark squares.} ({A move like} 12... Re8 {
looks a little passive. The following game is another good example of White
achieving his ideal setup in this structure.} 13. Bg5 $5 h6 14. Bd2 {[%csl Rg6,
Rh6]} a6 15. Qc2 Nh5 16. g4 $1 Nhf6 17. Kg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Yf2f4,Ya1e1]} Qc7
18. b3 Re7 19. f4 Rae8 20. Rae1 $16 {Black lacked space and was eventually
ground down in 1-0 (69) Peralta, F (2541) -Grigore, G (2507) Castellar 2004})
13. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Ge4][%cal Yc1g5] Not the only good move in the position,
but I like it because it highlights the downsides of Black's previous move and
his position, in general.} Be5 (13... Qe7 14. Bg5 $1 f6 15. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Re6]
[%cal Gf6f5,Ye4g5]}) 14. f4 f5 {A direct reply, typical for Morozevich's
dynamic style.} (14... Bd4+ {is safer than the game continuation, but White is
better, anyway, after} 15. Kh2 $14 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gg2g4]}) 15. fxe5 fxe4 16.
Rxf8+ Qxf8 17. e6 exd3 18. exd7 $16 {[%csl Yc1,Rd6,Rg8,Rh5] 1-0 (35) Topalov,
V (2784) -Morozevich, A (2731) Bilbao 2014}) (7... e5 {is a pretty simplistic
''Czech Benoni'' approach that can hardly be recommended here. White has a
clear plan to seize the initiative on the kingside with h3-g4, etc. The
following game of GM Erdos is an excellent example:} 8. h3 {[%cal Rg2g4]} Nh5 {
[%cal Yh5f4,Rg2g4]} (8... Ne8 {doesn't even stop} 9. g4 $16 {and if} f5 10.
gxf5 gxf5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Rxf5 13. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Ge4,Rg7][%cal
Gh1g1] the black position is close to strategically losing.}) 9. g3 Na6 ({
Black's main problem is that} 9... f5 10. exf5 gxf5 {runs into} 11. g4 $1 $16 {
[%csl Gd3,Rh7][%cal Gh1h7,Gf3g5]}) 10. Be2 Nc7 11. Nh2 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal
Yf1e3,Yf1g3,Gh2f1] A knight maneuver worth remembering.} a6 $5 {Black is ready
to sacrifice a pawn for positional compensation (light squares) , but White
doesn't take the bait.} 12. a4 Rb8 13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Rxb6 15. Nf1 $1 $16 {
[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf1e3,Ge2h5] Only now it Bxh5 a genuine threat because of
Ne3-f5, so Black cannot keep sacrificing the pawn anymore.} Nf6 16. h4 Bd7 17.
h5 Qe7 18. Ne3 $16 {White was fully in control in 1-0 (43) Erdos, V (2609)
-Kende, G (2246) Zalakaros 2011}) ({Finally,} 7... Na6 {is likely to transpose
after} 8. O-O Nc7 9. h3 e6 10. Re1 {- 7...e6 8.h3 Na6}) 8. h3 {The most
principled continuation, ruling out ...Bg4. It leads to well-researched
variations that we will examine below.} ({However, if you'd like to avoid deep
theory, you might prefer to transpose into the more strategic positions that
we already discussed in the previous and the first chapter.} 8. O-O exd5 9.
exd5 Bg4 10. h3 {[%emt 0:00:05] - Chapter} (10. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:01] - Chapter})
) {Black have two main directions here. The first one is to continue
developing and keep White guessing about his intentions:} 8... Na6 ({The
second one is} 8... exd5 {which we will cover in the following chapters.}) 9.
O-O Nc7 10. Re1 {Black can decide to play ...exd5 or ...e5 at any moment, so
our goal is to keep making useful developing moves. As a side with more space,
we should have more such moves than our opponent, so Black will eventually
have to make a decision.} Rb8 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gb7b5] Black is getting ready for
the b5-break.} (10... a6 {doesn't fit so well with Black's plan because he
usually wants to leave this square for his knight if White plays a2-a4.} 11. a4
{[%cal Rc7a6]} b6 12. Bg5 $5 {We can play the same way as in the main line.} h6
13. Be3 exd5 14. cxd5 $16 {[%cal Gd1d2]}) 11. Bg5 {This annoying pin will
provoke Black to play and weaken his kingside structure with ...h6.} ({
Alternatively, we could also prevent ...b7-b5 by playing} 11. a4 $5 {In
response, Black usually block the center with} e5 {[%cal Rb2b4] because White
will find it difficult to play for the b4-break when his pawn is already on a4.
Nevertheless, White keeps the upper hand in the following way:} 12. Bg5 $1 Na6
(12... h6 13. Bd2 {[%csl Rg6,Rh6]}) 13. Qd2 Nb4 14. Bb1 $1 {[%csl Gb1][%cal
Ga1a3,Rf7f5] We keep the bishop on the important diagonal. The rook can be
developed via a3.} b6 15. Nh2 a6 16. Ra3 $1 $16 {[%cal Ya3g3,Gg2g4,Gf2f4] As
we can see, White doesn't need to play on the queenside; his chances lie on
the kingside.}) 11... h6 12. Be3 exd5 (12... e5 {is even less principled here
since White can play on both flanks.} 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. a3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,
Gf2f4]}) 13. cxd5 $1 {In the main line, we recapture with the e-pawn, but it's
important to remember that here we do it with the c-pawn, entering the
classical Benoni structure. We don't mind it if Black plays} b5 {because his
queenside play fades in comparison to our central/kingside initiative, as we
can see from the game continuation:} 14. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rh6]} b4 (14... c4 $6
15. Bc2 {[%csl Rc6,Yd4][%cal Gf3d4,Gd4c6] and} b4 {are empty threats.} 16. Ne2
{[%csl Ra7,Rc4][%cal Ge2d4,Ge2g3,Ga1c1] and Black will have to reckon with a
serious weakness on c6, among other things.}) 15. Ne2 Kh7 16. Ng3 Nd7 17. h4 $1
{[%csl Rg6,Rh6,Rh7][%cal Gh4h5]} Ne8 18. h5 $40 {1-0 (39) Grigore,G (2472)
-Piat,J (2176) Creon 2006} *

