1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. h3 exd5
9. exd5 {This recapture is more promising than the alternative.} (9. cxd5 {
isn't wrong in principle, but in concrete terms,} b5 $1 {promises a
well-prepared black player theoretical equality.}) 9... Re8+ ({The
alternatives fail to impress.} 9... Qe7+ 10. Be3 Bh6 11. O-O Bxe3 12. Qe2 $1 {
[%csl Re7] This pin is the crucial difference compared to 9...Re8+ line. White
is always happy to sacrifice the f2-pawn to open the f-file for attack.} Nbd7 (
12... Bxf2+ $6 13. Qxf2 $40 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rg8][%cal Ga1e1,Yf2h4]}) 13. Rae1 a6
14. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Ye1][%cal Ge1e3]} b5 15. Rxe3 Qd8 {½-½ (46) Neiksans,A 
(2553) -Gdanski,J (2460) Sweden 2018. At the end of this logical sequence, I'd
like to suggest an equally logical improvement for White.} 16. Rfe1 {[%cal
Ye1e8]} bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nb6 18. b3 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rd6][%cal Gb3c4,Ye1e8] It may
not seem obvious at the moment, but the d6-pawn is a big liability for Black
in the long run.}) (9... Nfd7 $6 10. O-O Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Qd2
Nd7 14. Rae1 $40 {[%cal Gf2f4] 1-0 (31) Sokolov, I (2621) -El Taher, F (2535)
Sharjah 2014}) 10. Be3 {This is an important tabiya in the Benoni, which often
arises from alternative move orders. While Black has tried to neutralize
White's space advantage in many ways, the two with the best reputation are 10..
.Bh6 (covered in Chapter 8) and} Rxe3+ $5 (10... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] is a
simple continuation, but not without a strategic point. Black would like to
reduce his space disadvantage by trading a pair of knights on e5.} 11. O-O a6 {
Black tries to provoke 12.a4, but we don't have to oblige.} ({In case of the
immediate} 11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 Rxe5 {we can keep centralizing with} 13. Bf4 Re8
14. Qd2 a6 15. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rc8d7] so that Black is not in time
to complete his development.}) 12. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Yd2g5] It's crucial to ensure
control over the c1-h6 diagonal.} (12. a4 {would probably be a waste of time
in the view of} Ne5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Qd2 (15. Bg5 h6) 15... Nh5 $1
16. Bg5 f6 17. Be3 f5 18. Bg5 Qc7 {[%cal Gc8d7]}) 12... b5 {The principled
continuation. But we are ready to accept the gambit.} (12... Ne5 $6 13. Nxe5
Rxe5 {is already quite suspicious because of} 14. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]}
Qf8 15. f4 Re8 16. f5 $40 {1-0 (25) Zimmermann, R (2172) -Tortolero Hernandez,
C (1937) Caleta 2015}) 13. cxb5 Nb6 14. bxa6 Bxa6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 {[%cal Gb6c4]}
16. b3 {[%csl Rd5,Rd6] We have a typical Benko-gambit middlegame. Black is
hoping to drum up counterplay against the d- and a-pawns. However, in this
particular position, his compensation falls short because White is fully
mobilized.} Qa8 17. Rad1 Ne4 18. Nxe4 Rxe4 19. Qd3 Rb4 20. Bd2 $16 {½-½ (57)
Wang, J (2463) -Wang, T (2368) Charlotte 2021}) ({Finally, it's worth
mentioning the somewhat odd but playable idea} 10... Bf5 11. Bxf5 gxf5 {
[%csl Rf5,Rf7][%cal Gf6e4] Strategically, this looks awful for Black. However,
his idea to use the doubled f-pawn to secure control over the important
e4-outpost is not without merit from a dynamic point of view.} 12. O-O Ne4 13.
Nxe4 {I believe it's a good idea to take the opponent head on if we can earn
something in return.} ({There is also nothing wrong with the ''evasive''} 13.
Ne2 $5 {but we should be prepared for a manoeuvring battle after, say,} Nd7 14.
Qc2 Qf6 15. b3 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5,Yf6][%cal Ye2f4,Ya1e1,Yf4h5]}) 13... fxe4 14.
Nd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd1g4] This way, we can check directly whether the whole
idea behind 10...Bf5 works in concrete terms.} Nd7 15. Qg4 Nf6 16. Qh4 Nd7 17.
Qg3 Qf6 (17... f5 18. f3 $1 $16 {[%csl Re4,Rf5] Black has weakened his
kingside quite seriously, and this is the only way to exploit it.}) 18. Qg4 Ne5
19. Qxe4 $16 {Even a strong tactician like Shirov didn't manage to prove
compensation for the pawn in the game 1-0 (47) Huebner, R (2585) -Shirov, A 
(2580) Manila 1990. So, the whole line looks a bit suspicious for Black, after
all.}) ({Please refer to the next chapter to study the main line} 10... Bh6 11.
O-O Bxe3 12. fxe3) 11. fxe3 Qe7 {In both cases (here and after 10...Bh6, 11...
Bxe3) , Black forces White to compromise his pawn structure, although in this
instance, he pays the price in material. His reasoning is that White will find
it difficult to break the blockade on the dark squares, primarily the
e5-square. While this is largely true (at least in the short run) , White has
different ways to make his extra exchange count, as we will see.} 12. O-O {
As in the main line, we are more than happy to give away the e3-pawn to open
the e-file.} Nbd7 13. Qe1 $5 {[%cal Ye1h4] This rare move makes a lot of sense
as the queen can participate more actively on the dark squares.} ({In the main
line} 13. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1f2,Ga1f1] white goes for a typical rook-doubling on
the f-file. However, this also allows his opponent to play more aggressively
on the dark squares, for example} Nh5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yd7e5]} 14. g4 Ng3 15.
Rf2 h5 $1 16. Kg2 h4 17. Ne2 b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5,Rg2][%cal Gc8b7] 0-1 
(46) Cheng, B (2476) -Rapport, R (2654) Almaty 2022. Regardless of my engine's
reassurances that all is fine and dandy with the white position, I wouldn't
like to play like this if I don't have to.}) 13... Ne5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8f8]} (
13... Nh5 {is not nearly as problematic now that the g3-square is under
control. We can simply continue} 14. g4 Ne5 $5 15. Rd1 $1 {There's no need to
allow complications.} Nf6 16. Qh4 Bd7 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Rf3 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7]
[%cal Gd1f1] White is fully in the driver's seat since Black won't be in time
to put the other knight on e5. For example,} Be8 19. g5 Nd7 20. Ne4 $1 $40 {
[%cal Ge4f6]}) (13... b6 {[%cal Yc8b7] is the alternative way to complete
queenside development. However, it has a downside we can exploit.} 14. Kh1 Bb7
15. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga4a5,Ya1a8] Looking to open the a-file for the
rook or provoke other weaknesses.} a5 {[%csl Rb5,Rd6][%cal Gc3b5]} (15... Re8
16. a5 bxa5 17. Rxa5 a6 18. Ra3 $14) 16. Qh4 Ba6 (16... Re8 17. Nb5) 17. g4 $5
{[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg4g5] This is our standard plan in this line. White has an
active position, with good chances to outplay his opponent. For example,} Qxe3
18. Rad1 h5 19. g5 Nh7 20. Qe1 $1 Qxe1 21. Rdxe1 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rd6,Rf7][%cal
Ge1e7] Black will not have a lot of fun in the endgame.}) 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Rd1
$1 {A subtle move. The prophylactic idea behind it can be seen by comparing
the lines 15.Rf3 and 15...Qe7 below.} (15. Rf3 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf6d7,
Gd7e5]} 16. Qh4 Nxd5 17. Qxe7 Nxe7 $14) 15... Bd7 (15... Qe7 {[%csl Ye5][%cal
Gf6d7,Gd7e5]} 16. Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rf6d7] and now} Nxd5 {doesn't work because of}
17. Qxe7 Nxe7 18. Nb5 {[%csl Rd6]} Be5 19. Be4 $18 {[%csl Gd1,Rd6] which is
why we put the rook on d1 in the first place.}) 16. Rf3 $14 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7]
[%cal Ge1h4,Gg2g4,Gd1f1,Yg4g5,Yc3e4] ½-½ (61) Cuenca Jimenez,J (2555) -Silva
Lucena,C (2234) Linares 2022. White has a simple plan of improving his
position with moves like Qh4, g2-g4, Rdf1, etc.} *

