1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. h3 exd5
9. exd5 Re8+ 10. Be3 Bh6 11. O-O Bxe3 12. fxe3 {[%csl Rf6,Rg8][%cal Re1e8,
Yf1f7] Knowing how important the e-file is in this rather static Benoni
structure, we can understand Black's decision to force this structural change.
On the flip side, his king is weakened by the absence of the dark
squared-bishop, and White immediately obtains active play on the f-file.} Qe7 {
[%csl Ye5][%cal Yb8d7,Yd7e5] This is Black's most common continuation. His
plan is to exchange a pair of knights on e5 and recapture with the queen.} (
12... Rxe3 $2 {is not advisable in the view of} 13. Qd2 $40 {[%csl Rf7,Rg8]
[%cal Yd2h6]} Qe7 14. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Re3]} Rxf3 15. Rxf3 $16) (12... Nbd7 13. e4
{[%cal Gd1d2,Gd2h6]} Rf8 $5 {[%csl Yf7][%cal Gf6e8,Gd7e5,Ye8d6] is another
sensible idea for Black. With this move, he simultaneously clears the e8-d6
path for the knight (after Ne5 Nxe5, dxe5) and overprotects the vulnerable
f7-pawn.} (13... a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] prevents Nc3-b5 in some lines, but it also
wastes precious time.} 14. Qd2 Kg7 15. Rf2 $40 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7][%cal Ga1f1]})
14. Qd2 Ne8 15. Rf2 Ne5 (15... Qe7 {[%cal Yd7e5,Ye7e5] seems a little out of
place in this particular move order.} 16. Raf1 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Kh1 $1 {
[%cal Yc3e2,Ye2g1,Yg1f3] Queens are known to be poor blockers, and White will
have an easy time removing the black queen from e5 (with Ne2-g1-f3) . Black
would really like to get his knight on e5, but there is no route for it to get
there.} Bd7 19. Ne2 Ng7 {[%cal Gg7h5] 1-0 (47) Bluebaum, M (2619) -Petrov, M 
(2449) Chess.com INT 2019} 20. g4 $36 {[%csl Rd6,Rf7,Rg7][%cal Ge2g1,Gg1f3]
Black keeps struggling with a lack of space for his pieces.}) 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17.
Raf1 $14 {[%cal Ye8d6,Yf7f6,Yg8g7] White is better due to the pressure on the
kingside. However, as far as the blockades in this variations go, this one
looks quite solid for Black. White will need to show some skill to make
something out of his slight advantage. Let's see a sample line:} Kg7 18. Qe3 b6
19. Be2 f6 20. Qg3 Nd6 21. h4 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ye2g4,Yb2b3]}) 13. e4 Nbd7 ({
Once again, Black can rule out the Nb5-sortie with} 13... a6 {but his lag in
development gives strength to the thematic pawn sacrifice} 14. e5 $1 dxe5 15.
Qd2 $40 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gf3g5,Yd2h6]}) {We have reached the critical position of
this variation. White needs to decide how to proceed in the light of Black's
intention to strengthen his blockade by trading the knights via e5. I believe
it's a good idea to throw the spanner in the works with a quick e4-e5 pawn
sacrifice. We can do this in one of two ways.} 14. Nb5 $5 {[%csl Rd6][%cal
Gb5c7] This way, we win a tempo thanks to the unfortunate geometry of the
black rooks.} (14. e5 $5 {is obviously the other way to do it.} Nxe5 (14...
dxe5 15. Qd2 $36 {[%cal Ga1e1,Re5e4]}) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 ({After} 15... Qxe5 16.
Qf3 $36 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7][%cal Gf1f2,Ga1f1] Black felt like he had to return the
pawn with} Bf5 17. Bxf5 gxf5 18. Qxf5 Qxf5 19. Rxf5 Ne4 20. Nxe4 Rxe4 21. Raf1
Rf8 22. b3 $16 {0-1 (31) Salem,A (2690) -Sindarov,J (2609) Sharjah 2022}) 16.
Qf3 Kg7 17. Bc2 $5 $44 {[%cal Gd5d6,Yc2a4,Yf1f2,Ya1d1,Yd1e1] Black has many
decent possibilities, but White's initiative is undeniable.}) (14. Qd2 {
is the most common continuation, thoroughly tested in tournament practice and
correspondence chess. The final verdict is that after} Ne5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16.
Qf4 Kg7 17. Nb5 Rd8 {Black has good chances to hold the endgame, even being
down a pawn.}) 14... Rf8 (14... Ne5 {doesn't work now because of} 15. Nxe5 dxe5
16. d6 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Re8][%cal Gb5c7]}) 15. e5 $1 {This thematic pawn
sacrifice allows White to open the files and diagonals for his more active
pieces.} Nxe5 (15... dxe5 16. d6 Qd8 17. Bc2 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7][%cal Gb5c7]
looked like no fun for Black in 1-0 (54) Goryachkina, A (2478) -Majdan, J 
(2378) Reykjavik 2015}) 16. Nxe5 dxe5 (16... Qxe5 17. Qf3 {[%csl Gb5,Rd6][%cal
Ga1e1] is an even better version of Salem-Sindarov.}) 17. d6 Qd8 18. Qe2 {
Black is under serious pressure here. The best move is the unattractive} Ne8 {
All black pieces are on the eight rank, but he is hoping to win the d6-pawn.} (
18... e4 {probably only compounds Black's issues after} 19. Bc2 $16 {[%csl Yd6]
[%cal Ga1d1,Ye2e3]}) {We have two good continuations:} 19. Rad1 $5 {giving
support to the d-pawn,} ({and a more pragmatic} 19. Qxe5 {This move is based
on a strong tactical reply to the most obvious} a6 ({Black could also go for} 
19... Be6 20. Qxc5 Rc8 {but White preserves a slight edge with} 21. Qf2 $1 {
[%cal Gb5a7]} a6 22. Nd4 Qxd6 23. Nxe6 $14 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5]
thanks to his queenside majority and a better minor piece, regardless of how
Black recaptures.}) 20. Nc7 $1 Nxc7 21. dxc7 Qxd3 {The idea behind the piece
sacrifice is to win a tempo with} 22. Rad1 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Gd1d8] to get our
rook to the eight rank and threaten pawn promotion or checkmate. After a
virtually forced line:} Qxc4 23. Rd8 Be6 24. Rfd1 Rc8 25. Qd6 Rfxd8 26. cxd8=R+
Rxd8 27. Qxd8+ Kg7 28. a3 $14 {[%csl Ge6,Rg1,Rg7][%cal Gh7h5] we get an
endgame in which Black probably has reasonable drawing chances due to the
simplified material and somewhat exposed white king. Nevertheless, it's a
two-result endgame, where White can press with no risk, so we don't mind it.})
19... Be6 $1 {This is the best move, although not an obvious one.} ({Kicking
out the knight with} 19... a6 {is more straightforward. However, after} 20. Nc3
{it turns out that neither capture on d6 is good for Black. He should play} Be6
{anyway, but then 19...a6 doesn't seem useful.} (20... Nxd6 {is a poor choice
because of} 21. Qxe5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6]} Re8 22. Qxc5 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rd6,Rd8]}
) ({while} 20... Qxd6 {runs into} 21. Bf5 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Qb8 22. Bxc8 Qxc8
23. Qxe5 $40 {[%csl Re8,Rg8][%cal Gc3d5]}) 21. Rf2 Nxd6 (21... f6 22. Bc2 $16 {
[%csl Yd6][%cal Gc2a4,Gd6d7] leaves Black in a passive position.}) 22. Qxe5 Qc7
23. Bxg6 Ne8 $1 {This is Black's only chance to alleviate the pressure.
However, even the queen trade doesn't solve all his problems} 24. Qxc7 Nxc7 25.
Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rh7][%cal Gc3e4]}) 20. b3 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga8d8]
Instead of dealing with the knight and d-pawn, Black completes his development
first.} ({Once more,} 20... a6 {is less accurate on the account of} 21. Nc3 f6
(21... Nxd6 22. Qxe5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6]}) (21... Qxd6 22. Bxg6) 22. Be4 $36 {
[%csl Yd6]}) 21. Bc2 Rd8 22. Qxe5 a6 23. Nc3 Rxd6 {The annoying d-pawn has
finally been destroyed, but we can win another one back with} 24. Na4 Qc7 25.
Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Qxd6 Nxd6 27. Nxc5 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1d1] Black will suffer in
the endgame if he doesn't play} Rc8 28. Nxe6 fxe6 29. Rf6 $14 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,
Gc2,Gc4,Rd6] In endgames with pawns on both flanks, the bishop is usually
better than the knight. Add to this a better pawn structure, and we can
conclude that, despite the liquidated material, White keeps some winning
chances in the long run.} *

