1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal
Gc6d4] is a somewhat rare and provocative reply, but not a bad one, actually.}
({There aren't too many sensible alternatives for Black apart from those we've
already covered.} 6... c6 {is perhaps the last typical KID setup worth
checking.} 7. O-O a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (7... Na6 {is probably a more solid try,
transposing into positions covered in Chapter 4 after} 8. h3 e5 9. d5 ({or} 9.
Be3 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Rfe1 a5 13. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rd6]}) 9...
Nc5 10. Bc2 cxd5 11. cxd5 a5 12. Be3 Bd7 13. a4 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2]}) 8. h3 b5 {
[%csl Gd3,Gh3] This queenside operation can be successful in certain KID lines.
However, White is just about ideally placed to meet it here.} 9. Re1 {[%csl
Ge4][%cal Ye4e5]} Nbd7 ({In the event of} 9... bxc4 10. Bxc4 d5 11. Bb3 dxe4
12. Nxe4 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Rc6,Rc8][%cal Rc8g4] White has a pleasant advantage.})
10. e5 $36 Ne8 {After seizing space in the centre, we can proceed in several
ways. There is the aggressive} 11. Be4 ({as well as a more positional} 11. exd6
exd6 12. Bg5 Nef6 13. b3 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc8,Gd4][%cal Gd1d2]}) 11... Bb7 12. e6
$5 fxe6 13. Ng5 {[%csl Rb7,Re6,Rg8,Rh7]} Nc7 {which is based on the following
tactic:} 14. Nxh7 $1 Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Bxg6 Nf6 17. Qh4 $40 {[%csl Gg6,Rg8]
[%cal Yc1h6,Ye1e3,Ye3g3] with a strong kingside attack.}) 7. d5 {Black would
like to argue that he doesn't lose a tempo after this move because he can win
it back with} Nb4 {White doesn't want to part with his light-squared bishop at
such an early stage, so we'll have to move the bishop.} (7... Nb8 {is much
less logical. White can complete his development with ease now, obtaining a
sizeable advantage in all lines:} 8. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4]} e6 (8... c6 9. O-O Na6
10. Re1 Nc7 11. Bf4 $16 {1-0 (46) Afanasiev, N (2540) -Bilych, O (2288) Chess.
com INT 2021}) (8... a5 9. O-O Na6 10. Bc2 e5 {Black is down a tempo compared
to similar positions from Chapter 2.} 11. a3 c6 12. Be3 $16) 9. O-O Re8 10. Bg5
$5 h6 11. Be3 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd1d2]} Nbd7 12. Qd2 $16 {1-0 (57) Dardha,D 
(2520) -Lorenzo de la Riva,L (2417) Barcelona 2021}) 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Re8 {
[%csl Re4][%cal Ge6d5] This was played in the game 0-1 (30) Vrolijk, L (2433)
-Heimann, A (2574) Karlsruhe 2018. Black delayed exd5 to eliminate the cxd5
recapture from White's options.} ({The immediate} 9... exd5 {is less accurate
because White can take back with} 10. cxd5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]} a5 {[%cal Yb4a6,
Ya6c5] This seems to be necessary.} ({Black's issue here is that} 10... Re8 {
which occurred in 1-0 (40) Irizanin, R (2325) -Todorovic, B (2275) Vrnjacka
Banja 2007, can be met by} 11. a3 Na6 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. Qd3 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7]
[%cal Gf3d4] when Black would not have much to show for the shattered
queenside.}) 11. a3 Na6 12. Be3 Re8 13. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Gd5,Ge4] with a
typical pleasant edge for White.}) {I believe that the best way to relieve the
tension and circumvent the potential attack on the e4-pawn is to change the
structure with} 10. dxe6 $1 Bxe6 {followed by} 11. Nd4 {Now we have something
similar to the Classical variation. A few black pieces are in weird squares,
but this is only temporary. As the variations below show, Black can generate
counterplay against the white centre despite a certain lack of operating space.
The two main variations in my analysis are} Nc6 ({and} 11... Bd7 {[%csl Re4]}
12. f3 Nh5 {[%cal Gg7e5,Gd8h4] This is another provocative knight move.
Black's play in this line is obviously based on purely tactical considerations.
As I noted earlier, we should always check whether we can take the opponent's
plan head on. So, let's look at} 13. g4 (13. Be3 {is an apparently more
restrained option, but it allows Black to complicate matters with} c5 $1 (13...
f5 {looks tempting but after} 14. Qd2 f4 15. Bf2 Be5 16. Rfd1 {[%cal Gc4c5,
Ga2a3,Gb2b4] White's queenside play comes quicker than whatever Black tries on
the kingside. For example,} Ng3 17. c5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd7]}) 14. Ndb5 Bxb5 15.
Nxb5 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Bf6 $1 {[%cal Yh5g7,Yg7e6]} (16... Bg7 17. g4) 17. Nxd6 Bd4
$1 {[%csl Rd6,Re3] Black holds on thanks to tactics.} 18. Bxd4 Qxd6 $132 {
[%csl Yf4][%cal Yh5f4,Yb4a2,Yb4c6,Yc6d4]}) 13... Nf6 {[%csl Rg4] Was it worth
spending two tempi to provoke a weakness on the kingside? This question never
has a simple answer. I believe that, if we manage to consolidate the centre
and follow it up with Kh1 and Rg1, the g2-g4 advance can only be in our favour.
} 14. Be3 d5 $5 {[%csl Re3] This breakout tactic is a direct way to ''punish''
White for weakening his position.} ({Alternatively, Black could play} 14... h5
15. g5 Nh7 16. f4 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf1f2,Gd1d2] but this continuation doesn't
guarantee that he will not get gradually squeezed.}) {After the principled
reply} 15. a3 dxe4 16. axb4 exf3 17. Rxf3 Nxg4 18. Bf4 {[%csl Yd4,Yf4,Yh2] it
doesn't look like Black has full compensation for the piece, objectively.}) 12.
Be3 {Now we are in more familiar territory. This resembles a KID/Maroczy bind
hybrid with the pawn on c7 instead of e7. White will keep a slight but stable
advantage if he plays his cards right over the next 3-5 moves. Let's examine a
logical continuation:} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 a6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Yd6d5,Yb7b5]} 14. Qd2 c6 {
[%cal Gd6d5,Gb7b5]} 15. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5] This should be a no-brainer, even if
we weaken some squares on the queenside. Otherwise, Black gets serious
counterplay with ...b7-b5. Here are some possible continuations:} d5 (15... a5
{[%csl Yb4,Yc5]} 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. Rfe1 Nd7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Bd3 $1 {[%cal
Gd3c2,Gb2b3] As in many positions we've seen in the Neo-Seirawan variation,
the bishop is placed perfectly on the b1-h7 diagonal.} Nc5 20. Bc2 Rad8 21. b3
$14 {[%csl Gb3,Rg7][%cal Ge1e3,Ge3g3,Yh2h4,Yf2f4,Yc3e2,Ye2d4]}) (15... Rc8 16.
Rad1 c5 $5 17. Be3 Ng4 18. Bg5 $14) 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. e5 Nd7 (17... Ne4 {
is worse because of} 18. Qe3 Bf5 19. f4 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Ge2f3,Ga1d1] The
e4-knight is not as secure as one might think.}) 18. f4 f6 {[%csl Re5] This
pawn break allows Black to simplify matters in the centre and limit White's
advantage to a minimal one.} 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge2f3,
Gd4e5]} *

