squares on the queenside. Otherwise, Black gets serious counterplay with ...
b7-b5. Here are some possible continuations:} d5 (15... a5 {[%csl Yb4,Yc5]} 16.
Rad1 Qe7 17. Rfe1 Nd7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3c2,Gb2b3] As in many
positions we've seen in the Neo-Seirawan variation, the bishop is placed
perfectly on the b1-h7 diagonal.} Nc5 20. Bc2 Rad8 21. b3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rg7]
[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3g3,Yh2h4,Yf2f4,Yc3e2,Ye2d4]}) (15... Rc8 16. Rad1 c5 $5 17. Be3
Ng4 18. Bg5 $14) 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. e5 Nd7 (17... Ne4 {is worse because of} 18.
Qe3 Bf5 19. f4 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Ge2f3,Ga1d1] The e4-knight is not as
secure as one might think.}) 18. f4 f6 {[%csl Re5] This pawn break allows
Black to simplify matters in the center and limit White's advantage to a
minimal one.} 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge2f3,Gd4e5]} *

